---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---
<Base
  lang="en"
  title="vibebook — sync + resume your AI coding sessions across machines"
  description="The npm CLI half of vibebook: sync Claude Code + Copilot Chat sessions to a private GitHub repo, then resume them on any machine. Companion to the vibebook Claude Code plugin which adds digest + recall."
>
  <section class="hero container">
    <h1>Your AI sessions, portable across every machine you code on.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      <strong>vibebook</strong> is the npm CLI that syncs your Claude Code
      and VS Code Copilot Chat sessions to a private GitHub repo, then lets
      you <strong>resume</strong> any session on any machine. Pair it with
      the optional <a href="https://june9593.github.io/vibebook-plugin/">vibebook
      Claude Code plugin</a> for in-session digest + recall.
    </p>
    <div class="badges">
      <span class="badge">npm install -g <code>vibebook</code></span>
      <span class="badge">Claude Code · Copilot Chat</span>
      <span class="badge">MIT</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cta-row">
      <a class="btn-primary" href="#install">Install</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="https://github.com/june9593/vibebook">View on GitHub</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container">
    <h2>The pain it solves</h2>
    <p class="lede">
      You start debugging a Kubernetes pod on your laptop, hit lunch, walk
      to a meeting on a different floor, open your desktop — and your
      Claude session is stuck on the laptop. So you start over: paste the
      logs, re-explain the cluster topology, hope the new session catches
      up before you've burned an hour of context.
    </p>
    <p class="lede" style="margin-top: var(--space-5);">
      Or: your Friday-afternoon session debugged a flaky test, you ship the
      fix, then on Monday morning a different machine starts a new session
      and re-derives the same root cause from scratch.
    </p>
    <p class="lede" style="margin-top: var(--space-5);">
      vibebook keeps every session under <code>~/.vibebook/session-repo/</code>
      and pushes it to your private GitHub repo. Any machine that's pulled
      can <code>vibebook resume &lt;sessionId&gt;</code> and pick up where
      another machine left off — same context, same files-read, same
      decisions, same dead ends.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="container">
    <h2>Two superpowers</h2>
    <div class="three-col" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;">
      <div class="feature-card">
        <h3><code>vibebook sync</code></h3>
        <p>
          Walks <code>~/.claude/projects/</code> and your VS Code Copilot
          Chat storage, copies new sessions into the spool (with the
          original <code>.jsonl</code> preserved alongside rendered
          <code>.md</code> + <code>.raw.json</code>), commits, and pushes
          to a per-device branch on your private GitHub repo.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multi-device aware: each laptop pushes to its own branch and a
          GitHub Action deterministically merges them onto <code>main</code>.
          Optional encryption via a transparent git clean/smudge filter —
          your repo can be private without trusting GitHub with raw text.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="feature-card">
        <h3><code>vibebook resume &lt;id&gt;</code></h3>
        <p>
          Copies a session's <code>.jsonl</code> from the spool into
          <code>~/.claude/projects/&lt;encoded-cwd&gt;/&lt;newId&gt;.jsonl</code>
          and prints the <code>cd &lt;project&gt; &amp;&amp; claude --resume &lt;newId&gt;</code>
          command to run.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each resume is a <strong>fork</strong> — the new copy gets a fresh
          sessionId so two devices resuming the same source can continue
          in parallel without colliding when their spools sync up. The fork's
          origin is recorded so digest tooling can later group same-source
          threads.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="dark-section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Cross-device resume — an illustrative scenario</h2>
      <p>
        Friday, 4pm, on your laptop. You're three hours into debugging a
        flaky Kubernetes integration test. Claude has read 14 files, run
        a dozen <code>kubectl</code> commands, ruled out three suspected
        root causes, and finally narrowed it to a clock-skew assumption
        between two pods. You're tired. You quit.
      </p>
      <p>
        Saturday morning, on your desktop. You sit down with coffee and
        run:
      </p>
      <pre style="background: var(--deep-dark); color: var(--ivory); padding: var(--space-5); border-radius: var(--r-md);">vibebook sync                            # pull anything new from your other machines
vibebook list-sessions --since 2d        # find yesterday's session
vibebook resume 1f2c3d                   # copy + emit `claude --resume`</pre>
      <p>
        vibebook fetches your laptop's branch, finds yesterday's session in
        the spool, copies the <code>.jsonl</code> into the desktop's
        <code>~/.claude/projects/</code>, rewrites <code>/Users/laptop-me</code>
        paths to <code>/Users/desktop-me</code> (configured once via
        <code>vibebook config --map-path</code>), and prints:
      </p>
      <pre style="background: var(--deep-dark); color: var(--ivory); padding: var(--space-5); border-radius: var(--r-md);">Session forked: 1f2c3d-... → 8a7b6c5d-...
Continue with:
  cd /Users/desktop-me/work/k8s-cluster &amp;&amp; claude --resume 8a7b6c5d-...</pre>
      <p>
        You run that. Claude opens with all 14 files still in context,
        the three ruled-out hypotheses still in the conversation, and
        the clock-skew lead waiting for your next prompt. You don't
        re-explain. You don't re-derive. You just pick up where Friday
        you left off — on a different machine, from a different chair,
        with the second cup of coffee.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container" id="install">
    <h2>Install</h2>
    <p>Requires Node 20+.</p>
    <pre style="background: var(--deep-dark); color: var(--ivory); padding: var(--space-5); border-radius: var(--r-md);">npm install -g vibebook
vibebook init</pre>
    <p>
      The wizard walks you through the private GitHub repo URL, optional
      encryption setup, and per-device branch naming. After that,
      <code>vibebook sync</code> on any machine pushes new sessions and
      pulls everyone else's, and <code>vibebook resume &lt;id&gt;</code>
      lets you continue any of them locally.
    </p>
    <p>
      Want digest + recall on top? Install the optional Claude Code plugin:
    </p>
    <pre style="background: var(--deep-dark); color: var(--ivory); padding: var(--space-5); border-radius: var(--r-md);">/plugin marketplace add june9593/vibebook-plugin
/plugin install vibebook</pre>
    <p>
      Plugin and CLI share <code>~/.vibebook/session-repo/</code> — install
      one, both, or neither, in any order.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="container">
    <h2>CLI commands</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Command</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook init</code></td><td>Interactive wizard. Clones your private repo to <code>~/.vibebook/session-repo/</code>, sets up the device branch.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook sync</code></td><td>Extract new Claude Code + Copilot sessions on this machine, commit, push.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook list-sessions [--project] [--since] [--device]</code></td><td>List sessions in the spool, filterable for resume.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook resume &lt;sessionId&gt;</code></td><td>Fork a spool session into <code>~/.claude/projects/</code>, print <code>claude --resume</code> command.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook config [--map-path FROM=TO]</code></td><td>Read or modify <code>~/.vibebook/config.json</code> (e.g. cross-device path map).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook list</code> · <code>show</code> · <code>cat</code></td><td>Browse the spool from the shell.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook crypt &lt;action&gt;</code></td><td>Manage the git clean/smudge encryption filter.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook workflow</code></td><td>Install the cross-device merge GitHub Action.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook doctor</code></td><td>Health check (CLI / npm / git-crypt / plugin / spool format).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>vibebook upgrade</code></td><td><code>npm install -g vibebook@latest</code> wrapper.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section class="container">
    <h2>Files written</h2>
    <p>Everything lives under <code>~/.vibebook/</code>:</p>
    <ul style="color: var(--olive-gray); padding-left: var(--space-6); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <li><code>session-repo/</code> — git-tracked, pushes to your private GitHub repo</li>
      <li><code>session-repo/raw_sessions/&lt;tool&gt;/&lt;project&gt;/&lt;date&gt;/*.&#123;md,raw.json,jsonl&#125;</code> — synced session copies plus the original <code>.jsonl</code> (preserved for resume)</li>
      <li><code>session-repo/.vibebook/index.json</code> — per-session entry index</li>
      <li><code>config.json</code>, <code>passphrase</code>, <code>repo-salt.json</code> — CLI's local config</li>
      <li><code>resume-forks.json</code> — registry mapping forked sessionIds to their origin</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin-top: var(--space-4);">
      <code>book/</code> (chronicles + topics + the catalog) is written
      by the optional Claude Code plugin, not the npm CLI. The CLI never
      spawns an LLM — it's pure transport + I/O.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="container">
    <h2>Sibling project: vibebook plugin</h2>
    <p>
      The companion <a href="https://june9593.github.io/vibebook-plugin/">Claude
      Code plugin</a> is what turns synced sessions into a searchable book.
      It adds two slash commands:
    </p>
    <ul style="color: var(--olive-gray); padding-left: var(--space-6);">
      <li><strong><code>/vibebook</code></strong> — digest sessions into <strong>chronicles</strong> (one per work thread, AI-first frontmatter) and <strong>topics</strong> (mid-grain subsystem indexes).</li>
      <li><strong><code>/vibebook-recall</code></strong> — three-stage progressive recall before new work: project topic list → topic chronicles → full bodies. Lets agents stand on past learnings instead of rediscovering them.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The plugin works without the npm CLI (digest local sessions only)
      and the npm CLI works without the plugin (sync + resume only).
      Together they give you both <em>cross-device</em> and
      <em>cross-time</em> portability.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="container" style="padding-bottom: var(--space-24);">
    <h2>Project links</h2>
    <ul style="color: var(--olive-gray); padding-left: var(--space-6);">
      <li><a href="https://github.com/june9593/vibebook">GitHub source (npm CLI)</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/vibebook">npm package</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/june9593/vibebook/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md">Changelog</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/june9593/vibebook/issues">Issues / feedback</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://june9593.github.io/vibebook-plugin/">Sibling project: vibebook Claude Code plugin (digest + recall)</a></li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted small" style="margin-top: var(--space-6);">
      MIT licensed · Built by <a href="https://github.com/june9593">@june9593</a>
      · 168 vitest tests · Optional encryption via git clean/smudge filter.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
